Annotation of resistance genes/determintants

Query: GCF_000240185.1_ASM24018v2_genomic

Produced with bacannot pipeline

08 September 2020

1 About

Resistance genes or resistance determinants confer to the bacteria the ability to tolerate or resist some antibiotics or antimicrobials. Which means, these characteristics makes the bacteria less susceptible to its effects. Resistance determinants were predicted using AMRFinderPlus and CARD RGI. Additionally, we scanned the genome with ARGminer database which is an online resource for the inspection and curation of ARGs based on crowdsourcing as well as a platform to promote interaction and collaboration for the ARG scientific community.

AMRFinderPlus is a binary distributed by NCBI that allows users to query the National Database of Antibiotic Resistant Organisms (NDARO). This is a NCBI curated database that aggregates resistance genes from other databases such as Resfams, CARD, ResFinder, Pasteur Institute Beta Lactamases and others. For more information please read the following link. NCBIs efforts were done in order to standardize and confer reliability to AMR predictions.

CARD RGI is a tool which enables the detection of new variants and mutations that confer resistance to antibiotics, it analyzes genome or proteome sequences under three paradigms: Perfect, Strict, and Loose (a.k.a. Discovery). The Perfect algorithm is most often applied to clinical surveillance as it detects perfect matches to the curated reference sequences and mutations in the CARD. In contrast, the Strict algorithm detects previously unknown variants of known AMR genes, including secondary screen for key mutations, using detection models with CARDs curated similarity cut-offs to ensure the detected variant is likely a functional AMR gene.

ARGminer is used in the workflow in order to provide some more diverse insights about the resistance genes found. It can not be used as the sole source of prediction, but it may be a useful contribution for analyses and AMR descriptions because it tries to aggregate and create nomenclature standards between databases.

About the BLASTs:

  • AMRFinderPlus and ARGminer are searched in a manner that it is possible to filter alignments based on coverage and identity, for those we have used the following:
    • Blast % identity: > 90%
    • Blast % query coverage: > 90%
      • For blasts against gene sequences predicted by Prokka, alignments are filtered in a two way manner so they cover at least 90% of the reference gene sequence and the of query sequence at the same time valid for ARGminer
  • CARD RGI results are not filtered in these manners because they have their own detection models thresholds obtained by curation

3 CARD RGI

Below it is summarized the results obtained with RGI. Roughly, it can be divided into two main categories:

  1. Perfect hits
    • detects perfect matches to the curated reference sequences and mutations in the CARD
  2. Strict hits
    • detects previously unknown variants of known AMR genes, including secondary screen for key mutations, using detection models with CARDs curated similarity cut-offs to ensure the detected variant is likely a functional AMR gene

Obs: CARD RGI tool always tries to annotate functional AMR genes, however, depending on the assembly, a not functional gene may yet be annotated. There for, users are advised to double check genes annotated under Strict category.

3.1 Perfect hits

Perfect hits are genes that CARD guarantee its functionality. Which means that these genes are likely functional and might be conferring resistance to the bacteria. The drug classes found to be targeted by the AMR genes found are shown below:

  • Drug Classes targeted by the query genome:
    • aminoglycoside antibiotic
    • carbapenem
    • cephalosporin
    • macrolide antibiotic
    • monobactam
    • No specific target
    • penam
    • penem
    • peptide antibiotic
    • rifamycin antibiotic
    • sulfonamide antibiotic
    • tetracycline antibiotic

4 ARGminer

ARGminer is an online resource for the inspection and curation of ARGs based on crowdsourcing as well as a platform to promote interaction and collaboration for the ARG scientific community. We put this database here in the report and annotation in order to support the initative and to help it go towards nomenclature simplification. Genes are scanned via BLASTp since ARGminer is a protein-only database. This alignment is summarized in table 4.1.

It must be used with caution. Remender, it is a super new database thus it is rapidly changing and may yet contain errors.

5 Prokka

Additionally, Prokka generically annotates a few proteins that are related to any type of resistance. One must take caution when evaluating this result because this annotation can be very generic and therefore not so meaningful. Because it uses hmms, it can happen to annotate a multidrug resistance efflux pumps but it must be checked whether it is correctly annotated or functional. These are showed in Table 5.1.
